.\CHANGELOG.md:10:### Fixed — URP material crash guard in AssetSwap
.\CHANGELOG.md:11:- **Prevented a live material crash path on HRV2/URP when a swapped bundle material uses legacy shaders** — `TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle` now validates the resolved material shader before assigning it to `RenderMesh`. Materials whose shader name is not prefixed with `Universal Render Pipeline/` and that do not expose SRP batcher support via `FindPassTagValue` are skipped from live material assignment, while mesh swaps still proceed when valid. Skipped bundles log once (`[AssetSwap] skipped material swap for X: shader Y not HRV2-compatible`) and fallback to no-op material assignment. Crash-risk runtime writes are therefore prevented without blocking mesh-only swaps. File: `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`.
.\CHANGELOG.md:14:- **Per-frame Unity error flood `The AssetBundle '…sw-rep-clone-engineer' can't be loaded because another AssetBundle with the same files is already loaded`** — `AssetSwapSystem.LoadBundle` called `AssetBundle.LoadFromFile` and, when the LRU cache (max 10) evicted+Unloaded a bundle that Unity still considered loaded (Unload lag / scene-transition skip), the next frame's re-load threw and Unity logged the error. Because the swap retries every pending request each frame, this repeated forever — **740 occurrences** in a single skirmish run, flooding `Player.log` and degrading the game. Fixes in `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`: (1) **already-loaded recovery** — `LoadBundle` now catches the "already loaded" throw and reuses the existing handle via `AssetBundle.GetAllLoadedAssetBundles()` (matched by bundle name), re-caching it so later passes hit the cache and never re-call `LoadFromFile`; (2) **negative-result cache** (`_permanentlyFailedBundles`) — a bundle that yields no usable Mesh/Material (the 13 #986 90-byte stubs) or hard-fails to load is marked permanently failed and skipped on every later frame (logged once, then silent), cleared on `ScheduleReset` so hot-reloaded fixed bundles retry. Live-verified after deploy (build hash `CEA2362E…`, clean skirmish): `Player.log` "already loaded" count **740 → 0** (entire 2273-line run, 0 occurrences, 0 clone-engineer mentions, 0 AssetBundle errors). Working swaps intact — **306 `entity swap result=True`**, ground units `swapped 100/100` across 17264 matching entities, `sw-rep-clone-engineer` cim swap `result=True`. File: `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`.
.\CHANGELOG.md:15:### Fixed — SW building bundles now use URP Lit shader to prevent SRP batch crash
.\CHANGELOG.md:16:- **Switched procedural Star Wars building bundle material shader from Built-in `Standard` to URP `Universal Render Pipeline/Lit`** with fallback to `Universal Render Pipeline/Simple Lit` during assetbundle build, and switched tinting to `SetColor("_BaseColor", tint)` to keep `Hybrid Renderer V2` SRP batching compatibility.
.\CHANGELOG.md:17:- Rebuilt all 12 Star Wars building bundles on branch `feat/sw-building-bundles-20260531` using headless `Unity 2021.3.45f1` from `scripts/unity/unity-assetbundle-builder` and confirmed the build log includes `Universal Render Pipeline/Lit`.
.\CHANGELOG.md:19:### Fixed — SW building stub bundles built real (#982)
.\CHANGELOG.md:20:- **12 remaining Star Wars BUILDING bundles were 90-byte stubs** — `sw-assembly-line`, `sw-blast-wall`, `sw-durasteel-barrier`, `sw-guard-tower`, `sw-heavy-foundry`, `sw-mining-facility`, `sw-processing-plant`, `sw-skyshield-generator`, `sw-tech-union-lab`, `sw-tibanna-refinery`, `sw-vulture-nest`, `sw-weapons-factory`. As placeholders they kept those buildings native in-game and made the swap engine (#986) re-load a useless stub every frame, flooding the AssetSwap log with "another AssetBundle with the same files is already loaded". Built REAL Unity 2021.3.45f1 AssetBundles for all 12 (each ~46-47 KB, up from 90 B) — distinct procedural SW-styled building silhouettes (factory / wall / tower / refinery / mine / lab / shield-emitter / vulture-nest / blast-barrier) on a faction-tinted Standard material (CIS grey / Republic white). New self-contained Editor builder `BuildSwBuildingBundles.cs` (meshes generated in-C# via `CombineInstance` of box primitives — no Blender / glTF dependency), promoted to `scripts/unity/unity-assetbundle-builder/Assets/Editor/`. Built headless with the canonical `Unity.exe 2021.3.45f1` (`-batchmode -nographics -quit -executeMethod BuildSwBuildingBundles.Build`), exit 0, bundle headers verified `UnityFS ... 2021.3.45f1`. Bundle filename == `visual_asset` key == Addressable key; all 12 keys were already present in `addressables.yaml` / `asset_pipeline.yaml` (no CRC/hash fields, so no registration change needed). NOT deployed — deploy happens at reconcile.
.\CHANGELOG.md:22:- **EnvironmentThemeSwap bootstrapped for gameplay scenes (`Task #985`)** — Added `src/Runtime/Graphics/EnvironmentThemeSwap.cs` and hooked it into runtime bootstrap (`ProcessWorldReadyCoroutine` + scene-load hooks) so gameplay scene loads apply planet-specific skybox materials and call `DynamicGI.UpdateEnvironment`. Main menu scenes remain excluded. Added placeholder mappings in code for `tatooine` (tan), `naboo` (blue), `umbara` (dark), and `coruscant` (city-orange) until real skybox bundles are added.
.\CHANGELOG.md:24:- **Corrected diagnosis:** runtime `#986` mesh swap does not touch launch-time incoming-enemy previews. The preview path is outside `WaveInjector`/`AssetSwapSystem` scope; runtime code under `src/Runtime` only shows pack screenshot/gallery sprite loading and menu/theming helpers, and no `WavePreview`/`incoming wave`/render-target symbols in runtime UI assembly.
.\CHANGELOG.md:29:- **Wrong swap archetypes for cims, buildings, and aircraft (live `0 succeeded` → `39 succeeded`)** — The #975 archetype guesses returned 0 RenderMesh-bearing entities, so the `RenderMesh AND <archetype>` swap query matched nothing and these categories logged `batch complete — 0 succeeded, 30 failed` while ground units swapped fine. A live entity-dump (bridge `queryEntities`, active skirmish) revealed the ground truth: (1) cims carry **`Components.Citizen`** (live count 58) with RenderMesh on the same entity — the previous guess `Components.Worker` matched only 2 singletons; (2) DINO **buildings** carry `Components.BuildingBase` (575) but **no RenderMesh on the parent** — the mesh lives on a CHILD entity referenced via `Unity.Entities.LinkedEntityGroup`; (3) `aerial_fighter` resolved to `DINOForge.Runtime.Aviation.AerialUnitComponent` which DINO never tags (0 live entities; no native fliers). Fixes: cims/worker/citizen → `Components.Citizen` (`PackStatMappings`); `aerial_fighter` swap archetype → `Components.SiegeUnit` (real renderable archetype, count 162; `AssetSwapSystem`); and a new `CollectRenderMeshChildren()` that, when a parent archetype carries no RenderMesh, walks `LinkedEntityGroup` to swap the RenderMesh-bearing children (`AssetSwapSystem`). Also: `GameControlCli` `entities` verb now prints the full JSON archetype dump. Live-verified after deploy: warfare-starwars pass `batch complete — 39 succeeded, 13 failed` (was 0 succeeded); `sw-cis-droid-pilot` cim `swapped 51/51 result=True`; `sw-cis-command-center` / `sw-cis-droid-factory` / `sw-clone-barracks` / `sw-rep-vehicle-bay` buildings each `swapped 100/100` via the child-walk. The 13 remaining failures are 90-byte STUB bundles with no usable mesh (pre-existing #101 asset gap), not archetype failures. Survey: `docs/sessions/entity-archetype-survey-20260531.md`. Files: `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`, `src/Runtime/Bridge/PackStatMappings.cs`, `src/Tools/GameControlCli/Program.cs`.
.\CHANGELOG.md:94:- **AssetSwap THE "units look native" fix: mesh-substring filter was rejecting 100% of entities (#101).** Even after the reflection fix, every unit stayed native — live logs showed `swapped 0/100 entities (skipped 100 non-matching meshes)` for every mapping. Root cause: with an authoritative archetype filter already applied, the SECONDARY mesh-name substring filter (`VanillaMappingToMeshSubstrings`, e.g. `Swordsman`/`Militia`/`Knight`) was used as a hard *reject*, but those hand-guessed substrings do not match DINO's real mesh vocabulary (`swordsmen`, `royal_sword_2`, `bomj_*`, `harpy_*`, `undead_*`, `natives_*`), so 0 entities passed and no mesh was ever written. Fix: when an archetype filter is present it is authoritative — swap every entity the narrowed `EntityQuery` returns and ignore the substrings (which now serve only as a fallback targeting signal when there is no archetype filter). Live-verified: `swapped 100/100 … skipped 0` across MeleeUnit/RangeUnit/SiegeUnit/Aerial (66 positive swaps, 0 zero-swaps) — units now render their Star Wars meshes. (`src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`)
.\CHANGELOG.md:96:- **AssetSwap ground-unit swap: ComponentType→Int32 reflection error (#101, "units look native" BUG A).** `AssetSwapSystem.TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle`'s archetype-narrowed path threw at runtime — `Object of type 'Unity.Entities.ComponentType' cannot be converted to type 'System.Int32'` → `result=False` ("swapped 0/100" for ground units e.g. `sw-cis-magna-guard`). DINO's Unity 2021.3 `EntityManager` exposes the non-generic `GetSharedComponentData` in TWO overloads — `(Entity, ComponentType)` AND `(Entity, int typeIndex)` — and the `FirstOrDefault` lookup (which accepts either) could bind the Int32 overload, then invoking it with a boxed `ComponentType` threw. Fix: detect the bound overload's second-parameter type and pass `ComponentType.TypeIndex` (int) when it wants `System.Int32`, else the `ComponentType`. (`src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`)
.\CHANGELOG.md:97:- **AssetSwap aerial units: `aerial_fighter` no longer stuck in DIAGNOSTIC MODE (#101, BUG B).** `vanilla_mapping='aerial_fighter'` produced no archetype filter (PackStatMappings intentionally maps it to null for stat injection — `AerialSpawnSystem` owns aerial behaviour) AND no mesh-name substrings → `sw-tri-fighter`/`sw-nantex-fighter` skipped the swap. Fix: new `AssetSwapSystem.TryResolveSwapArchetype()` resolves `aerial_fighter` to `DINOForge.Runtime.Aviation.AerialUnitComponent` for the visual swap (PackStatMappings stays null so stat injection still defers to `AerialSpawnSystem`); added aerial mesh-name substrings (`Aerial/Air/Flying/Fighter/...`) as a fallback targeting signal so the swap proceeds even before `AerialSpawnSystem` tags the entity. (`src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`, `src/Runtime/Bridge/PackStatMappings.cs`)
.\CHANGELOG.md:99:- **AssetSwap buildings: structures no longer stuck in DIAGNOSTIC MODE (#101, building fix).** Pack buildings (e.g. `sw-cis-command-center`, `sw-rep-vehicle-bay`, `sw-cis-droid-factory`) registered their swap with **no** `vanilla_mapping` — `BuildingDefinition` had no such field and `ContentLoader` passed null — so every SW structure fell into DIAGNOSTIC MODE and kept rendering as the native royal/undead building. Fix: added `BuildingDefinition.VanillaMapping` (YAML `vanilla_mapping`); `ContentLoader` now passes it, defaulting to the generic `building` mapping when omitted; `AssetSwapSystem.TryResolveSwapArchetype()` maps `building` → `Components.BuildingBase` (the universal vanilla building archetype) and a `building` mesh-substring set was added as a refinement. Building stat injection is unaffected (resolution lives in the swap path, not `PackStatMappings`). (`src/SDK/Models/BuildingDefinition.cs`, `src/SDK/ContentLoader.cs`, `src/Runtime/Bridge/AssetSwapSystem.cs`)
.\CHANGELOG.md:102:- **Star Wars live mesh-swap exits DIAGNOSTIC MODE (#964).** `AssetSwapSystem.TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle` previously referenced a non-existent `BundleToVanillaMeshMap` and tried to match optional mesh-name substrings by *bundle filename*, so every Star Wars bundle fell into DIAGNOSTIC MODE and no entity swap ran. The optional mesh-name refinement now keys off the request's `vanilla_mapping` value via `VanillaMappingToMeshSubstrings` (aligned 1:1 with `PackStatMappings.VanillaMappingToComponentType`). DIAGNOSTIC MODE is now entered only when there is **no** targeting signal at all — neither a resolved archetype filter nor mesh-name substrings — so a populated `vanilla_mapping` (already present on all 30 SW units; aerial intentionally skipped) lets the archetype-narrowed swap proceed. The mesh-name filter loop is guarded so archetype-only mode swaps every entity the narrowed query returns. Mesh/material lookup remains robust via `ResolveReplacementAssets` (exact-name → prefab renderer → `LoadAllAssets<Mesh>/<Material>` fallback — never the bundle key). Key audit: all 30 SW unit `visual_asset` keys resolve in `addressables.yaml`; 14 reference real (>40KB) bundles. Runtime builds netstandard2.0 exit 0; all 31 AssetSwap tests pass.
.\CHANGELOG.md:104:  - **Gap A — building swaps now register WITH a `vanilla_mapping`.** `ContentLoader.RegisterAssetSwaps` previously registered every building swap with a null `vanilla_mapping`, so the runtime `AssetSwapSystem` saw "no targeting signal" and skipped them in DIAGNOSTIC MODE. It now resolves a mapping per building in priority order — explicit `building.vanilla_mapping` → `building_type` (command/barracks/resource/defense/tower/wall/research) → generic `"building"` — and threads it into `AssetSwapRequest.VanillaMapping`. New `BuildingDefinition.VanillaMapping` (`vanilla_mapping:` YAML field) makes the targeting declarative.
.\CHANGELOG.md:105:  - **Gap B — cims (citizens/workers, `bomj_*` meshes) now have a registration path.** Cims are modelled as units carrying `vanilla_mapping: cims`, so the existing unit registration path wires their swap with no new registry or schema. New `packs/warfare-starwars/units/cims.yaml` reskins them to SW worker units (`rep_clone_worker` → Clone Engineer, `cis_worker_droid` → Pilot Droid) using real (non-stub) bundles.
.\CHANGELOG.md:107:  - `PackStatMappings.VanillaMappingToComponentType` gained entries for `cims`/`worker`/`citizen` (→ `Components.Worker`, candidate archetype — verify via entity dump) and `building`/`command`/`barracks`/`resource`/`economy`/`defense`/`tower`/`wall`/`research` (→ `Components.BuildingBase`). `AssetSwapSystem.VanillaMappingToMeshSubstrings` gained matching `bomj`/worker and building (castle/barrack/farm/tower/wall/…) mesh-name substrings so swaps still exit DIAGNOSTIC MODE via the secondary mesh-name filter when the archetype type does not resolve. Maps/skybox are Phase 2 (out of scope). Runtime builds netstandard2.0 exit 0; new registration + mapping tests added (`FullWorldConversionSwapTests`, `PackStatInjectorTests`).
.\CHANGELOG.md:117:- **Real meshes + AssetBundles for 19 previously-stub Star Wars units (#964 / #946 fallback).** Replaced 896/1092-byte stub `model.glb` (and absent meshes) with Blender-generated clean-room parametric silhouettes (walkers, fighters, hovertanks, spider/tripod droids, troopers, gunship), converted to FBX and built into Unity 2021.3.45f1 AssetBundles (filename = `visual_asset` = Addressable key). Covers marquee gaps: `sw-general-grievous`, `sw-rep-at-te-walker`, `sw-tri-fighter`, `sw-aat-walker`/`sw-cis-aat`, `sw-v19-torrent`, `sw-jedi-knight`, `sw-cis-spider-droid`, `sw-rep-laat-gunship`, `sw-droideka`, plus arc/commando/sniper/magna-guard/medical/b1-squad/wall-guard/stap/barc. Bundles are 82–153 KB real geometry (not 90-byte stubs); render-proofs in `docs/screenshots/model-previews/sw-procedural/`. Acquisition strategy (Sketchfab token path, BF2/Frostbite extraction steps, OSS/CC0 sources, legal posture) documented in `docs/sessions/sw-asset-acquisition-20260530.md`. New tooling: `unity-assetbundle-builder/generate_sw_procedural.py`, `render_proof.py`, `Assets/Editor/BuildSwMissingBundles.cs`. Placeholder-grade — meant to be upgraded by higher-fidelity Sketchfab/BF2 sources when the user supplies a token or runs the extractor.
.\CHANGELOG.md:137:- **Realistic-GFX mode Phase 2 — PBR material upgrade for the `High` graphics tier (Manor-Lords-like lift).** Builds on the Phase-1 URP post-process PoC (#976). When `[Graphics] Tier = High`, DINOForge now upgrades swapped unit/building materials to the URP/Lit physically-based shader and bumps quality settings; `Tier = Vanilla` remains a strict passthrough. CODE-READY (visible result needs real PBR textures from #973-BF2 + a deploy).
.\CHANGELOG.md:138:  - **`GraphicsMaterialUpgrader` (`src/Runtime/Graphics/GraphicsMaterialUpgrader.cs`)** — `Upgrade(Material, assetKey)` produces a new `Universal Render Pipeline/Lit` material that carries over the base albedo map + tint and layers in declared PBR maps (albedo `_BaseMap`, metallic+gloss `_MetallicGlossMap`, normal `_BumpMap`, AO `_OcclusionMap`, emission `_EmissionMap`) with the matching shader keywords (`_METALLICSPECGLOSSMAP` / `_NORMALMAP` / `_OCCLUSIONMAP` / `_EMISSION`). Sets a sensible metallic/smoothness baseline even when no maps exist, so surfaces gain proper specular response under High. Graceful fallback to the original material when tier is Vanilla, when URP/Lit is unavailable, or on any error (never throws, never breaks a swap).
.\CHANGELOG.md:140:  - **AssetSwap hook (#964 path)** — `AssetSwapSystem.TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle` now runs the resolved replacement material through `GraphicsMaterialUpgrader.Upgrade(..., assetName)` before applying it to live RenderMesh entities, so SW-swapped units pick up the PBR upgrade automatically when High is active.
.\CHANGELOG.md:141:  - **Quality-settings bumps (`GraphicsMode`)** — High tier raises shadow resolution (VeryHigh), shadow distance (≥150), cascades (4), and MSAA (4x), captured-and-restored against a vanilla snapshot so toggling back to Vanilla fully reverts. The upgrader's `ActiveTier` is driven from `GraphicsMode` in lock-step with the Phase-1 post-process toggle (reversible).
.\CHANGELOG.md:146:  - **Star Wars aerial content (real meshes).** Republic `rep_gunship_bay` (Gunship Landing Platform → produces `rep_laat_gunship` + `rep_v19_torrent`, mesh `sw-rep-gunship-bay`) and CIS `cis_droid_hangar` (Droid Starfighter Hangar → produces `cis_tri_fighter` + `cis_nantex_fighter`, mesh `sw-cis-hangar-bay`); wired existing `cis_vulture_nest` to produce `cis_tri_fighter`. New aerial units `rep_laat_gunship` (mesh `sw-rep-laat-gunship`) and `cis_nantex_fighter` (mesh `sw-nantex-fighter`), both referencing real proven-render bundles.
.\CHANGELOG.md:193:- **Star Wars bundles shipped primitive-placeholder prefabs instead of real meshes (#101/#947)** — The shipped `warfare-starwars` AssetBundles wired 64/75 bundle prefabs to Unity built-in primitive meshes (Cube/Capsule/Sphere, `fileID:10202`), so even a perfect in-game Harmony swap rendered cubes. Root cause: `*.fbx`/`*.glb`/`*.obj` are gitignored, so in a fresh worktree the only committed mesh source is `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/raw/<asset_id>/model.glb` (the `!packs/*/assets/raw/*/model.glb` allowlist); the intended pipeline (`convert_models.py` Blender GLB→FBX → `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels` → `BuildAssetBundles`) was never reproduced end-to-end in the worktree, and the primitive-only generators (`GenerateStarWarsPrefabs.cs`/`BuildAll.cs`, which *skip existing* prefabs) had poisoned the prefab dir. Fixes:
.\CHANGELOG.md:194:  - Added `unity-assetbundle-builder/convert_real_models.py` — worktree-relative Blender converter that imports only the **real** committed GLBs (vertex-count gate skips the 21 stub `model.glb` files that are 896/1092-byte, 8–24-vertex placeholders) into `Assets/Models/*.fbx`. Result: 15 real FBX (855–104,389 verts) converted, 21 stubs correctly skipped.
.\CHANGELOG.md:196:  - Regenerated all prefabs from the real FBX (Unity 2021.3.45f1 batchmode, `-noUpm`): **14 of 36 SW unit/building bundle keys now reference real MeshFilter/MeshRenderer + materials** (the rest fall back to primitives only where no real source GLB exists in the repo).
.\CHANGELOG.md:197:  - Rebuilt the AssetBundles and updated the 3 newly-real bundles in `packs/warfare-starwars/assets/bundles/`: `sw-cis-spider-droid` 43,768B→1,467,170B, `sw-rep-clone-commander` 44,382B→207,814B, `sw-rep-at-te-walker` 44,197B→96,885B (the other 11 real-mesh bundles were already real). Bundle-mesh content externally verified by loading the rebuilt bundles back in Unity (`VerifyBundleMesh`): spider-droid maxVerts=48,515, clone-commander 8 meshes maxVerts=1,751, at-te-walker 36 meshes, droideka maxVerts=65,541 — vs the primitive control `sw-rep-clone-pilot` at a single 550-vert capsule. Deployed to the live game pack and verified by SHA-256 match.
.\CHANGELOG.md:201:- **Update-check threw `MethodNotFound: JToken.ToString(Newtonsoft.Json.Formatting)` at runtime** — `RuntimeDriver` logged `[RuntimeDriver] Update check result delivery failed: ... Method not found: string Newtonsoft.Json.Linq.JToken.ToString(Newtonsoft.Json.Formatting)` whenever the update check tried to persist its 24-hour throttle timestamp. Root cause: `UpdateChecker.PersistLastCheck()` called the `JToken.ToString(Formatting)` **instance** overload, which is absent from the Unity-bundled, stripped `Newtonsoft.Json` 13.0.2 (`<game>_Data/Managed/Newtonsoft.Json.dll`) that the Runtime both compiles and runs against in the BepInEx/Mono context (a second, full 13.0.4 copy lives in `BepInEx/plugins/`). Fix (`src/Runtime/Updates/UpdateChecker.cs:294`): use the version-stable static `JsonConvert.SerializeObject(state, Formatting.None)` instead — the same static API the JSON-RPC bridge already uses successfully. Audited all of `src/Runtime` for sibling version-fragile Newtonsoft instance overloads; this was the only `.ToString(Formatting)` call (all other serialization already uses static `JsonConvert.SerializeObject`).
.\CHANGELOG.md:202:- **Aviation ECS systems crashed every frame: "This method should have been replaced by codegen"** — `AerialMovementSystem`, `AerialTargetingSystem`, and `AerialSpawnSystem` each used `Entities.ForEach(...).WithoutBurst().Run()` in their `OnUpdate`. `Entities.ForEach`/`Job.WithCode` REQUIRE the Unity.Entities DOTS source generator, which only runs inside the Unity Editor's compilation pipeline. `DINOForge.Runtime` is built `netstandard2.0` outside the editor (`dotnet build`), so codegen never replaces the lambda placeholder and it throws at runtime — flooding the log every simulation frame once `SimulationSystemGroup` ticks. Fixed by rewriting all three `OnUpdate` methods to the established manual `EntityQuery` pattern (cache the query in `OnCreate` with `EntityQueryOptions.IncludePrefab`, iterate `ToEntityArray(Allocator.Temp)`, `EntityManager.Get/SetComponentData`) — the same codegen-free approach used by `EntityQueries.cs` / `AssetSwapSystem.cs`. No `Entities.ForEach`/`Job.WithCode` remains anywhere in `src/Runtime/Aviation/`. Behavior (altitude lerp, nearest-enemy targeting, spawn-at-altitude, anti-air building sweep) is preserved exactly.
